\f1\fs30 \cf3 \cb1 \outl0\strokewidth0 To illustrate the disjointed system that has emerged, Grabell worked with ProPublica news app developer \cb10 Lena\cb1  Groeger to construct an interactive that showed the wide variations in the value of a workers' body parts between states. Calculating the value each state put on a lost arm or leg was no simple matter; reporters had to learn the intricacies of each jurisdiction\'92s unique set of complex rules and formulas. \'85. First, the state differences in workers\'92 compensation are vast, but when one also considers the different benefits per body part \'96 a hand versus an eye, for example \'96 the complexity increases fast. Our challenge was to convey this complexity in an engaging, easy to understand way. Our solution was to use the most ready metaphor: the human body. For each we built a human form, each limb proportionally sized according to a specific dollar amount. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://propub.ca/work-limb"}}{\fldrslt \cf11 http://propub.ca/work-limb}}) Users could sort the figures by state or by the compensation amount for a particular limb. Because our eyes can quickly see differences in the human form, this provided a perfect visual tool to convey a very complicated dataset. \
Each limb was sized programmatically by calculating the maximum amount a worker could be paid for that limb in that state compared to the national average. Because a single updated number in the dataset would reconfigure every limb size, it was crucial for us to be able to update this graphic using a computer program and not painstakingly by hand. We also gave readers the ability to search for a particular state and zoom in to more easily compare it to the national average.\
