\f0\fs30 \cf2 More than a century ago, labor and industry came together and formed a historic compact called workers\'92 compensation to take care of injured workers and their families. Workers gave up their right to sue in exchange for prompt medical care and enough of their wages to get by while they recovered.
\f4\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\i\b\fs30 \cf2  
\f4\i0\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 But a ProPublica and NPR investigation found that over the past decade, state after state has been dismantling its workers\'92 comp system, often at the behest of big business and insurance companies.
\f4\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 Stories by ProPublica\'92s Michael Grabell and NPR\'92s Howard Berkes detailed how the changes have resulted in disastrous consequences for many of the hundreds of thousands of people who suffer serious injuries at work each year. Workers have been evicted from their homes, denied prosthetic devices their doctors recommended or left in precarious situations when their home health aides were taken away. 
\f4\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 Grabell also gathered a mountain of data, combing through the laws of all 50 states to document how the laws worked, where they fell short and how drastically they differed from one another 
\f5 \'96
\f0  even across state lines. One particularly telling piece of that data showed the maximum compensation workers could receive for the loss of each body part in each state, D.C. and the federal system. Reporters computed this value using each state\'92s complicated formula.
\f4\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 News Applications Developer Lena Groeger used this data to compose a compelling visual story, \'93Workers\'92 Comp Benefits: How Much is a Limb Worth,\'94 which dramatically showed the arbitrary and sometimes absurd discrepancies in benefits. 
\f4\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 Her interactive graphic uses schematic images of the human body, one for each state, that are visually similar to the chart of beef cuts sometimes shown in butcher shops. Moving your mouse over each body part reveals the compensation that state provides for the parts compared to the national average. By allowing people to quickly scan rows and rows of human forms \'96 each body part sized according to how much the state pays in compensation benefits \'96 the graphic conveys at a glance the huge disparity in state benefits.
\f4\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 Comparing states, readers can see the often preposterous differences between states for the same injury. Nevada, for instance, doles out up to $859,634 for the loss of an arm, while Alabama\'92s top payout is just $48,840.
